Emoji popularity also varies by region. While ğŸ˜‚ and â¤ï¸ are universally beloved, other emojis have local fame. The emoji for cricket ğŸ might be commonly used in India, whereas an American might have to dig to even find that on their keyboard. A ğŸµ (tea) might be more used in Britain, whereas ğŸ¶ (sake) might be more used in Japan. These differences reflect local culture, sports, foods, and customs sneaking into emoji use. If you peek at Twitter data, you'd likely find *clusters of emoji usage that correspond to geography* â€“ like how the ğŸŒ® might spike on Taco Tuesday in the US, or how certain flag emojis surge during international events like the World Cup.

